<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18501125-174">
               <interp inst="t18501125-174" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18501125"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18501125-174" type="date" value="18501125"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18501125-174-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-174-18501125 t18501125-174-offence-1 t18501125-174-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>174. <persName id="def1-174-18501125" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-174-18501125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-174-18501125" type="surname" value="COURTENAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-174-18501125" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN COURTENAY</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18501125-174-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18501125-174-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18501125-174-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="housebreaking"></interp>, feloniously breaking and entering the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18501125-name-977" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-977" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-977" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-977" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18501125-174-offence-1 t18501125-name-977"></join>Edward Jones</persName>, and stealing 144 metal taps, value 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18501125-name-978" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-978" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-978" type="surname" value="DOULTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-978" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18501125-174-offence-1 t18501125-name-978"></join>John Doulton</persName> and another.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-979" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-979" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-979" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-979" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 29, High-street, Lambeth, and am in the service of Mr. John Doulton, and his partner, Mr. Watts—they an potters—I sleep in that house five nights in a week, and the other two I go into the country—besides the room I occupy, there are rooms used as store-rooms. On Saturday, 2nd Nov., I was at the premises till six o'clock in the evening—I was the last in the house—I locked it up, and took the keys with me—I had locked the outer and inner doors, and had the keys with me—the inner door leads from the front-room into the back-room—the front-room down-stairs and the back-room up-stairs are what I occupy—in the back-room down-stairs, were these taps, some sponge, and other valuable things—there is no way to the back-room but through the front-room—when I returned on the Monday morning, I found the outer door still fast—I unlocked it, and went in—the lower front-room has a window, which was open—it was shut when I left on Saturday—I saw a parcel of chips lying under the inner door—it had been cut, both on the door-post and opposite the lock, to facilitate the admission of an iron bar—the door was open, and the fastening was lying by it—I found an iron bar lying in the passage—I compared it with the indents—they cor<lb></lb>responded I missed from the back-room twelve dozen taps, which I had received from Mr. Hickman—I saw them on the Saturday, about six o'clock—it is my opinion that these (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) are the same taps, with the name filed out—there are marks of a file—those taps I left, had the name of "Doulton and Watts" on them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this house yours? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It belongs to Messrs. Doulton and Watts, and there are seventy or eighty persons employed on the premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who enters that house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No one but myself; the work<lb></lb>men do not come in there—there are workshops besides that dwelling-house—the prisoner was never employed there—I do not know him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-980" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-980" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-980" type="surname" value="HICKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-980" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HICKMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Birmingham, and am a brass-cock founder. I was in the habit of supplying Mr. Doulton and his partner with brass taps—I sent them thirty dozen about a week or ten days before 2nd Nov.—hose produced by the officer are a portion of the stock I sent to Messrs. Doulton and Watts, to the best of my knowledge—they are our manufacture, and I have the punch that they are marked with—I supply no other house with the same sort of goods—here is the pattern they are cast from—they are all marked with the warehouse mark, a W.—these have not the marks on them, they have been filed off—the names are on the handles, and these handles are thinner and rougher than ours—we never turn out goods in this state.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You never made any of these taps for any other house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, not of this sort—I have supplied other houses with other</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185011250189"></xptr>
               <p>descriptions of taps—I supply this house with this description by their order—these are made of yellow metal—I never supplied any other house with any of this metal.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-981" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-981" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-981" type="surname" value="GARFORTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-981" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS GARFORTH</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, L</hi> 151). From information on Friday, 8th Nov., I went to Mr. Simpson's shop in Lower-marsh, Lambeth—I found there three dozen of these brass taps—I afterwards went to the shop of Henry Fisk, a general outfitter for tobacconist's shops in the New-cut, where I found two dozen and eleven of these taps—I found one tap at the house of Mr. Bliss, a gas-fitter—on Saturday, 9th Nov., I saw the pri<lb></lb>soner go into a public-house in the New-cut—I went in after him, and said, "You must consider yourself in my custody for having had a quan<lb></lb>tity of brass taps in your possession"—he said, "I have been to Doulton and Watts this morning"—he did not say for what purpose—I had not mentioned the name of Doulton and Watts to him—I asked him how he came by them—he said he bought them at a sale in Leicester-square—I asked him if he knew the man he bought them of—he said he was a dark Jew-looking man, with a thin nose—I asked him if he had a catalogue of the sale—he said, "No," the sale had commenced about an hour before he got there—he afterwards said he bought them at Jones's sale-room on Monday the 4th, in the evening—there is an auctioneer of that name—there are two auction-rooms, but Mr. Jones's is not in Leicester-Square, it is two doors down a passage—the prisoner described the place where he bought them—he said, "Jones's is at the further end of Leicester-square," which would be the further end from the police-court—I went to another auction-room, Mr. Thomas's—I got a catalogue from Mr. Thomas".</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> There is another auction-room in Leicester-square? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, Mr. Thomas's, which is three doors from Green-street; that is in the square—I was informed by the foreman that the prisoner had been to Messrs. Doulton's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-982" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-982" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-982" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-982" type="given" value="HENRY ADAMS"></interp>HENRY ADAMS SIMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a marine-store dealer, of the New<lb></lb>cut, Lambeth. On Monday, 4th Nov., I saw the prisoner in my house about twelve o'clock in the day—I have known him fifteen years, he attends sale-rooms—I never knew anything wrong of him—he buys lots, and sells them in the trade to ironmongers, marine-store dealers, and furni<lb></lb>ture dealers—he called on me that Monday about twelve o'clock, and said he was going to Jones's sale-room for twelve dozen of taps to be sold, what would I give him for them—I know Jones's sale-rooms; they are called in Leicester-square; they are within two doors of it—I do not know whether they have any window which looks into Leicester-square—I said I could not tell what to give for them unless I saw them—on the following Thurs<lb></lb>day he brought me a sample tap—I told him I would take three dozen at 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a dozen—he came back in about two hours, and said he had sold three dozen to Fisk, and six dozen to another place, and I should have the three dozen, and I had them—he came back about five o'clock, and brought the three dozen with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You have known him fifteen years? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he has been dealing at my shop—I always thought him a respectable young man—it is a common thing for parties to buy things at sales, and sell them at a profit; that is the way he has got his living—he was well known in the trade—all the brokers in the Cut know him—I never bought taps of him before.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185011250190"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HICKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> What is the price of these taps? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Eight and sixpence a dozen, with two and a half per cent. off and carriage paid, which reduces them to about eight shillings and twopence a dozen,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-983" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-983" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-983" type="surname" value="FISK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-983" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM FISK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman to my uncle, Henry Fisk, a shop-fixture dealer in the New-cut. On 6th November the prisoner came to our shop, between ten and twelve o'clock in the morning—he brought me one tap, and asked me whether the taps would suit my uncle—he said he had about three dozen—he came again about one o'clock and brought thirty-four more—he had left the sample one—he said he would call on Saturday, about two o'clock, to ascertain whether my uncle would have them—I said, "They will not suit the governor; they are not long enough"—he came on Saturday, and I told him they would not suit—the officer came to our shop on Friday evening—when the prisoner called on Saturday I told him to take them away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say he came on Wednesday with a sample, and he came again later and brought thirty-four? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I told him to leave them and come again on Saturday—he did not come to our place on the Satur<lb></lb>day—he was opposite, and I told the officer that was the man, and he went and took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then when was it you told him the taps would not suit? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think it was on the Thursday—he came again on the Thursday, the next day, and then he said, "I will call again on Saturday"—he asked me if he might leave them, as he was going on further—no time was fixed for his coming on Saturday—he said he would come about Saturday—he asked seven shillings and sixpence a dozen for them—he did not tell me where he got them—I did not ask him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long have you known him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The last six years—he has been in the habit of dealing at our house almost every day—he has sold us things—it is customary for persons in that way to buy things at auctions and pawnbrokers—I am sure he said he would call on Thursday, and he did call—I knew him to be a very good, fair-dealing man—I never knew anything against his character; if he got any profit he would be satisfied—I have been in the Cut seven years, in my uncle's service—he has been known at our house fifteen years—I do not know where he lives—when I saw him on the Saturday he was walking along on the other side of the way.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you in the habit of buying new articles from him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Sometimes—I never bought any taps of him—he was in the habit of selling cheap—the slightest profit would satisfy him—he would bring counting-house railings and other things.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-984" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-984" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-984" type="surname" value="AARON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-984" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE AARON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Mr. Bliss, of 20, New-cut, Lambeth. On 6th Nov. I saw the prisoner at my master's shop with one of these taps as a sample for my employer to look at—I rather think he said how many he had got, but I do not remember—he said he had a quantity of taps for sale—I think he called several times during the day, to know whether Mr. Bliss approved of them—he called on Friday and saw Mr. Bliss, who said he would purchase them—I was present and advised Mr. Bliss to purchase them, as they would suit us—he agreed to purchase six dozen, at seven shillings and sixpence a dozen—two guineas were paid for them, which is a fair value—we could purchase the same articles new for a halfpenny more each—I do not know whether we have ever bought taps</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185011250191"></xptr>
               <p>like these—we have had new taps from Birmingham—I consider they might have been purchased at seven; shillings and sixpence, or eight shillings.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long have you known the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Some years—he has been in the habit of dealing at our house, buying and selling—I never heard anything wrong of him—he has been allowed to select goods in our shop—he has sold such goods as he might buy at sales.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What articles has he sold at your shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Goods of various descriptions—we are gas-fitters—I rather think we have bought taps of him before, with other goods; not very recently—my master is in the miscellaneous way, he purchases other things—the prisoner lives some where close by us—he said he purchased these taps at a sale-room; I am not certain whether he said Jones's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-985" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-985" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-985" type="surname" value="HONNOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-985" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HONNOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a porter in the employ of Mr. Jones, in Lei<lb></lb>cester-street, Leicester-square, an auctioneer—there is no other auctioner of that name in Leicester-square—I have been in his employ four years—I do not recollect seeing the prisoner there—the regular days for our sales are Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Fridays—I cannot undertake to say the prisoner has not been there—I recollect Monday 4th Nov.—there was no sale there that evening nor on that day—there has been no taps like these sold at Mr. Jones's—there was no sale on Tuesday 5th Nov., nor any taps sold of this description—there was a sale on Wednesday 6th— —there were no taps of this description sold in that week, nor the week before—I was present at all the sales all the time—about twelve months ago we had an ironmonger's stock sold—we sold some taps, but not twelve dozen.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You cannot swear that taps might not have been sold without your knowledge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not in the sale—they might have been sold in the sale-room, that is done at times—persons come to the sale with lots and sell them without their being in the catalogue—persons attending other sales knowing that dealers are in our room, come in the afternoon and sell them by private contract in the room—the sale-rooms are open other days for men to bring goods in—the articles are on view on Wednesday morning—the rooms are open on Monday and Tuesday for taking in articles—articles might not on these days be sold by private contract—we begin on Monday night to make the catalogue, and we allow no one to enter except to bring goods—as many as half-a-dozen persons might be there—I cannot undertake to say that goods might not be sold by private contract—brokers and persons of that sort meet at our doors and do business—Mr. Thomas's auction-rooms are in the square—their sales are on Mondays and Thursdays.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you at Mr. Jones's rooms on that Monday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I live there—I am always there—except on auction days no persons are allowed to come there to traffic—they are not allowed to be in the room to make a sale—if two dealers meet there to make a sale, they would be told to go down-stairs and settle it—I was there on the Tuesday—the sale commences on Wednesday at six o'clock in the evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501125-name-986" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-986" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-986" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-name-986" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD JONES</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I am the only person who occupies this house—I keep the key of the outer-door and of the room where the pro<lb></lb>secutor's goods are—I pay no rent nor taxes—I live on part of my master's premises—the family never sleep there—the prisoner did come to Doulton.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185011250192"></xptr>
               <p>and Watts—I am not certain on what day—Mr. Doulton told him it was in the hands of the police.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">GEORGE AARON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> On the Saturday on which the prisoner was apprehended, was he in your shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, in the morning—he came respecting the taps—I learned from him that he had seen Mr. Bliss—the officer had been to our house in the morning—the names of Doulton and Watts were mentioned, but Mr. Bliss had heard of this robbery before he went to look for the prisoner.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The prisoner received a good character.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18501125-174-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18501125-174-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501125-174-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
            </div1>
